/PGMOTZEY SHABBAT/XX526/XX/PR
/KAHAMAVDIL / THE ONE WHO DIVIDES/PR
/ITThis translation can be sung to the same melody as /MDShavuÚa Tov/XX./PR
/PR
May the one who divides/PR
between holy and plain,/PR
forgive our sins,/PR
and ease our pain./PR
Posterity and plenty/PR
add to our gain,/PR
like seashore sands,/PR
like stars at night./PR
/PR
The day moves on/PR
like palm treeÚs shade,/PR
I call to God/PR
who charts the way./PR
The watchman says,/PR
"The morn has come,/PR
and soon the night,/PR
yes, soon the night."/PR
/PR
Your justice strong/PR
as Mount Tabor,/PR
My sins forgive,/PR
my faults ignore./PR
Let me be pure,/PR
like long before,/PR
My blemish fade/PR
like passing night./PR
/PR
/SCN/XXOTE/XX. Composed by Rabbi Isaac ibn Ghayat, who lived in eleventh--
century Spain, for the conclusion of Yom Kippur, /ITHamavdil/XX hails the divine
power that allows us forgiveness, renewed vigor and redemption.    /SC/XXA.G./XX/PR
